hives to shed new light on how authors, their translators and their publishers collaborateAlexander von Humboldt was one of the most important scientists of the nineteenth century. Captivating his readers with his vibrant, lyrical prose, he transformed understandings of the earth and space by rethinking nature as the interconnection of global forces. This book argues that style was key to the success of these translations and shows how Humboldt’s British translators, now largely forgotten figures, were pivotal in moulding his prose and his public persona as they reconfigured his works for readers in Britain and beyond.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aNatural historyzGreat BritainxHistory. 0aNaturalistszGermany. 0aScience newsxHistoryx19th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aScience news. 0aScience publishingxHistoryx19th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aScience publishing. 0aSciencexHistoryx19th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aScience. 0aScientific literaturexTranslatingxGreat Britain. 0aScientific literaturexTranslatingxHistoryx19th centuryxGreat Britain. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311078043740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147443934340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474439343423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474439343/original  a978-3-11-078043-7  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK